# Controllers and services

Use with **`layered-express-modules.mdc`** (directory map, `sendSuccess`, `AppError`, Zod). This rule is the **mental model** and **naming** for the HTTP layer vs domain layer.

## Roles

| | **Controller** (“traffic cop”) | **Service** (“chef”) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Job** | HTTP only: parse context, call one service, format response | Business rules, workflows, Prisma/vendor I/O |
| **Input** | `req` (after `validate*`), `req.authUser` / `req.dbUser` | Plain typed objects (`userId`, DTOs, options) |
| **Output** | `sendSuccess` / throw `AppError` | Domain data or side effects; **no** `Request`/`Response` |
| **Reuse** | One route shape | Controllers, workers, webhooks, scripts |
| **Tests** | Often integration | Unit-test friendly (no HTTP mock) |

## Controller checklist

- Thin: **no Prisma** unless the team explicitly allows a trivial read (default: **services own DB**).
- **Throw** typed errors for expected failures; avoid ad hoc `res.status(...).json(...)` for business cases so **`errorHandler`** stays the single error shape.
- Transport-only steps stay here or in middleware (e.g. webhook signature verification, redirects) even if they are not “business rules.”

## Service checklist

- **Named exports**, `async function` per use case (or a small cohesive group).
- **Explicit** Prisma `create`/`update` fields—never spread raw client bodies into DB calls (**`security-auth-prisma.mdc`**).

## Service file naming

- Name files for **domain**, not the URL prefix. Example: authenticated “self” flows mounted under `/me` use **`session-user`**, **`session-profile`**, **`user-analytics`**—not **`me-*`**, which reads like a route segment and ages poorly if routes change.
- HTTP routes may still be `/me/...`; only **service filenames** avoid the `me-` prefix.

## Quick examples

```typescript
// Controller — wire HTTP to service (after validateBody)
export async function patchMe(req: Request, res: Response): Promise<void> {
  const data = await patchMeUser(req.dbUser!.id, req.body);
  sendSuccess(res, data);
}
```

```typescript
// Service — no req/res; lives in e.g. session-user.service.ts
export async function patchMeUser(userId: string, body: PatchMeBodyDto) {
  // prisma, rules, throw ConflictError / …
}
```
